  "prompt": "Can risotto be made using a rice cooker?",
  "response": "Yes, risotto can be made in a rice cooker, though the traditional method of making risotto involves constant stirring on the stovetop. Here's a basic approach for making risotto in a rice cooker:\n\n1. Saut\u00e9 your aromatics (onions, garlic) in a pan first\n2. Add rice and toast it briefly\n3. Transfer ingredients to the rice cooker\n4. Add broth gradually, stirring occasionally\n5. Let the rice cooker complete the cooking cycle\n\nKeep in mind that the texture may not be exactly the same as traditionally made risotto, which is known for its creamy, al dente consistency achieved through constant stirring. Rice cooker risotto might be slightly less creamy, but it's still a convenient method that produces a tasty result with less hands-on time.\n\nMany rice cookers now have specific risotto settings that can help achieve a more authentic texture. For best results, you may want to stir the rice a few times during cooking and add warm broth in stages.",
